    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3511081783" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3511081783" />
    <a title="Laura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/43285184-laura"><img alt="Laura" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1642337441p2/43285184.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3511081783?book_show_action=true">May 28, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura" href="/user/show/43285184-laura">Laura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781408813553" href="/book/show/9394255-mornings-in-jenin">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43285184-laura?shelf=all-time-favourites">all-time-favourites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43285184-laura?shelf=special-place-in-my-humble-heart">special-place-in-my-humble-heart</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43285184-laura?shelf=i-will-sell-my-soul-for-this">i-will-sell-my-soul-for-this</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43285184-laura?shelf=2021-favs">2021-favs</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43285184-laura?shelf=must-read-in-a-lifetime">must-read-in-a-lifetime</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/43285184-laura?shelf=cryfest-overload">cryfest-overload</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3511081783" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10101887559222951941"><b>
  <i>“Our bond was Palestine. It was a language we dismantled to construct a home.”</i>
</b><br/><br/>Mornings in Jenin is now a book I will recommend to everyone I know. I have this little bundle of books that I always talk about and wish everyone would read and this book has become one of them.<br/><br/>I had had it on my to be read list for some time now and the recent events in Palestine did help me picking it up now rather than later – Susan Abulhawa tells a heart-breaking family story from the first days of Israel’s op</span>
  <span id="freeText10101887559222951941" style="display:none"><b>
  <i>“Our bond was Palestine. It was a language we dismantled to construct a home.”</i>
</b><br /><br />Mornings in Jenin is now a book I will recommend to everyone I know. I have this little bundle of books that I always talk about and wish everyone would read and this book has become one of them.<br /><br />I had had it on my to be read list for some time now and the recent events in Palestine did help me picking it up now rather than later – Susan Abulhawa tells a heart-breaking family story from the first days of Israel’s oppression. <b>Although historical fiction, I accepted this book as a history lesson, one that taught me so much about the reasons why Palestine is still fighting today for their freedom. I can say for certainty that I will be reading her other books as well.</b><br /><br />The prose acts like an oxymoron to the plot: on one hand, the writing depicts a certain poetry, a chant and a melody I loved from the very first words I read, and on the other hand, these songs translate the atrocities of apartheid, ethnic cleansing and oppression. The writing is so impactful that I had to take many breaks, to let the words sink in, and to let Amal’s feelings go through me. I particularly felt sorrow during her move from Lebanon to the US. <b>I value a book that teaches me, I value books that shake my mind and give me a massive reality check, and Mornings in Jenin is a slap across the face when it comes to opening our eyes to facts.</b><br /><br /><blockquote>“We come from the land, give our love and labor to her, and she nurtures us in return. When we die, we return to the land. In a way, she owns us. Palestine owns us and we belong to her”<br />“The land and everything on it can be taken away, but no one can take away your knowledge or the degrees you earn”<br /><br />“He looked on in silence at the proof of what Israelis already know, that their history is contrived from the bones and traditions of Palestinians. The Europeans who came knew neither hummus nor falafel but later proclaimed them authentic Jewish cuisine." They claimed the villas of Qatamon as "old Jewish homes. They had no old photographs or ancient drawings of their ancestry living on the land, loving it, and planting it. They arrived from foreign nations and uncovered coins in Palestines earth from the Canaanites, the Romans, the ottomans, then sold them as their own "ancient Jewish artifacts." They came to Jaffa and found oranges the size of watermelons and said, "Behold! The Jews are known for their oranges." But those oranges were the culmination of centuries of Palestinian farmers perfecting the art of citrus growing.”</blockquote><br /><br />It is hard for me to truly explain how I feel about Mornings in Jenin, I am lacking words. Especially when it came to expressing love and gratitude, something well explained in the book. The constant juxtaposition between loving someone and fearing losing them was gut-wrenching, leaving me tearful, because I cannot even imagine a spark of this impossible dilemma. Not because I don’t want to but because <b>the author does an amazing job at reminding us, that Palestinians’ sorrow is deep into their roots and veins.</b><br /><br /><blockquote>“Thank you,’ I answered, unsure of the proper American response to her gracious enthusiasm. In the Arab world, gratitude is a language unto itself. “May Allah bless the hands that give me this gift”; “Beauty is in the eyes that find me pretty”; “May Allah never deny your prayer”; and so on, an infinite string of prayerful appreciation. Coming from such a culture, I have always found a mere “thank you” an insufficient expression that makes my voice sound miserly and ungrateful.”<br /><br />“Amal, I believe that most Americans do not love as we do. It is not for any inherent deficiency or superiority in them. They live in the safe, shallow, parts that rarely push human emotions into the depths where we dwell.”<br /><br />“It is the kind of love you can know only if you have felt the intense hunger that makes your body eat itself at night. The kind you know only after life shields you from falling bombs or bullets passing through your body. It is the love that dives naked toward infinity’s reach. I think it is where God lives.”</blockquote><br /><br />I will be reading Abulhawa other works, she has quickly become a voice I want to hear more from, and I hope this review might have convinced you to read this book as well.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10101887559222951941" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


