    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_95448337" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/95448337" />
    <a title="Richard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1047783-richard"><img alt="Richard" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1412391379p2/1047783.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/95448337?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard" href="/user/show/1047783-richard">Richard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer95448337" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer248411768040915947">I wanted to read Mornings in Jenin because I was looking for an artful corrective to the American media slant of Israeli/good, Palestinian/terrorist. Unfortunately, Mornings in Jenin is neither artful nor corrective; what it is is propaganda from the pro-Palestinian side in which, and for the most part Palestinian = good, Israeli = terrorist. That&apos;s half the problem, the other half is that it&apos;s not a very well written book, suffering from unmotivated shifts in point of view, considerable telling</span>
  <span id="freeText248411768040915947" style="display:none">I wanted to read Mornings in Jenin because I was looking for an artful corrective to the American media slant of Israeli/good, Palestinian/terrorist. Unfortunately, Mornings in Jenin is neither artful nor corrective; what it is is propaganda from the pro-Palestinian side in which, and for the most part Palestinian = good, Israeli = terrorist. That's half the problem, the other half is that it's not a very well written book, suffering from unmotivated shifts in point of view, considerable telling rather than showing, artistic corner-cutting by lifting whole passages from books and other documents while squeezing the story to match the reportage, a wildly leaping time frame, and purple prose. The author also seems to be unsure of just what story she wants to tell: coming of age, separation of twins, horrors of occupation, plight of women, and so gives us a smattering of all the above. In short, it's as much a mess as the middle-east itself. And like the middle-east it may not be an unmitigated disaster, but to paraphrase Cormac McCartthy, "it'll do until one shows up." <br /><br />So, what mitigates the disaster? It's a first novel, and Susan Abulhawa shows signs of being able to tell a story. The book succeeds in giving a face, voice, and humanity to Palestinians who are only seen, on this side of the water, as evil. It also lifts the veil on the horrors perpetrated by the Israeli government and military. There is a small amount of sympathy shown the Israeli side, but if Ms. Abulhawa had managed to give us a truly balanced look - showing both sides as mixed bags of humanity under unimaginable stress, then we'd have a book worth reading. <br /><br />I've given Mornings in Jenin one star. It's not a very good book, but more than that, I'm truly saddened by it - saddened because the Palestinian people live in an oppressive siege, because the Israelis can't seem to do any better than they have, because humanity is being wasted on both sides, and because Ms Abulhawa hasn't given us a better book - though I think a better book is in her.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="248411768040915947" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


