    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_82027703" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/82027703" />
    <a title="new_user" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1365355-new-user"><img alt="new_user" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1351189841p2/1365355.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/82027703?book_show_action=true">Dec 25, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="new_user" class="user" itemprop="url" name="new_user" href="/user/show/1365355-new-user">new_user</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1365355-new-user?shelf=first-reads">first-reads</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer82027703" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5793739227182875561"><i>Mornings in Jenin</i> is difficult to review because the normal tags do not apply. <i>Mornings</i> is near enough to non-fiction as makes no difference. Susan Abulhawa imagines the characters, but their feelings, motivations and the events of the novel draw from reality and weighs <i>Mornings</i> with significance. The brutalities in the novel are such that again and again one wonders, much as in war literature, &quot;How can people do this to each other?&quot; Heartrending doesn&apos;t begin to describe it. It physically hurts</span>
  <span id="freeText5793739227182875561" style="display:none"><i>Mornings in Jenin</i> is difficult to review because the normal tags do not apply. <i>Mornings</i> is near enough to non-fiction as makes no difference. Susan Abulhawa imagines the characters, but their feelings, motivations and the events of the novel draw from reality and weighs <i>Mornings</i> with significance. The brutalities in the novel are such that again and again one wonders, much as in war literature, "How can people do this to each other?" Heartrending doesn't begin to describe it. It physically hurts to know these things are true.<br /><br /><i>Mornings</i> brings history and culture to these happenings that the news media cannot. Abulhawa deftly guides the reader from the 40s to modern day Jenin without slowing the narrative through the use of non-linear narration, foreshadowing, etc. Readers hardly realize they're reading an intergenerational saga because we are aware of Amal, on whom the entire story hinges, almost from the beginning. Because of the author's clues, she is present in the narrative and developing in our minds even before she is born.<br /><br />Abulhawa also has a delight with words that is clear in her prose, where her imagery and unique metaphors are always fresh. She also has a ways of capturing powerful moments and scenes, imbuing each with emotion and meaning so one doesn't read in a vacuum. I can certainly see the comparison to <i>Kite Runner</i>, and I was impressed that the ending managed to carry some kind of resolution for the characters without solving the world's problems in thirty seconds. <br /><br />I wish there was a little less bias against Islam, but that was fortunately minimal. I also really liked the glossary of Arabic vocabulary at the back of the book. The narrative is peppered with Arabic words whose English translations would just seem jarring in their place and would not capture the same emotion, so I thought the glossary was a good idea.<br /><br />I recommend this book to anyone, really, since most readers have only a passing familiarity with the region or the conflict, in which the US is engaged. This is a pretty good introduction.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5793739227182875561" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

