  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1237629427" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1237629427" />
    <a title="Zanna" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22591633-zanna"><img alt="Zanna" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1512813535p2/22591633.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1237629427?book_show_action=true">Mar 26, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zanna" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zanna" href="/user/show/22591633-zanna">Zanna</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781408813553" href="/book/show/9394255-mornings-in-jenin">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=grt">grt</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=bechdel-pass">bechdel-pass</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=me-na-w">me-na-w</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/22591633-zanna?shelf=me-na-lit">me-na-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1237629427" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13545883017575425944">3.5 stars<br/><br/>I found this a heart-rending book; it upset me over and over because it reflects real histories. In general, I appreciate fictionalisations like this, because I understand and remember through emotional connections with characters. Susan Abulhawa successfully transforms real events in the genocidal invasion and occupation of Palestine into the story of one family’s experience here. I was already familiar with this history and was not surprised by any of the events, althought I was still</span>
  <span id="freeText13545883017575425944" style="display:none">3.5 stars<br /><br />I found this a heart-rending book; it upset me over and over because it reflects real histories. In general, I appreciate fictionalisations like this, because I understand and remember through emotional connections with characters. Susan Abulhawa successfully transforms real events in the genocidal invasion and occupation of Palestine into the story of one family’s experience here. I was already familiar with this history and was not surprised by any of the events, althought I was still upset and shocked.<br /><br />I had some issues with the descriptions of Dalia, the mother of the most central character, Amal. Dalia is a Bedouin woman and attention is drawn to the sedentary community’s prejudice towards her, (which somewhat mirrors the sedentarist racism against GRT people in the UK), which is good, but I am not sure I feel OK about the use of the word ‘Gypsy’ and descriptions of Dalia’s ‘wild and colourful’ personality, behaviour and clothing; Abulhawa’s reply to the community’s negative image of Dalia is exotification. She is taciturn and rather unassertive even before the Nakba and the devastating loss of her baby so we don't have much of her voice against others' views of her<br /><br />I felt uncomfortable that traumatised people are repeatedly described as ‘dead inside’; this discomfort reflects my privileged existence and insulation from many forms of trauma. One of the things I find really insightful and useful about the book is that some of the Jewish/Israeli characters who have had comparatively comfortable and privileged lives are able to be compassionate, generous, empathetic and so on, because trauma can make people less able to draw on such resources. Going further, the ways that some traumatised people (Palestinians) are able to continue being loving, communitarian, life-affirming is an even more great thing about the book.<br /><br />What I really didn’t like was the style of narration. I like the way experiences are described in interior narration, often in high sensory detail, down to the crunchy sound of dirt underfoot on a hard floor, but I dislike the author voice that comes between segments of interior narration. The fact is that I cannot process, for example Amal and her brother’s devastating losses intellectually – I can EITHER hear what such things are like to the victims in their own words, OR how an outside observer sees the effects of such experiences. The omniscient author voice narration that invasively pulls in and out of different characters’ consciousness in order to get the best view, like a piece of sophisticated sporting event coverage, made me progressively more motion-sick. I feel I should not have access to this commentary – if I really value Amal’s humanity, her testimony should be enough for me.<br /><br />Perhaps the intent behind this was for the text to <i>embody</i> <b>violation</b>. Radwa Ashour’s <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17678418.The_Woman_from_Tantoura" title="The Woman from Tantoura by Radwa Ashour" rel="nofollow noopener">The Woman from Tantoura</a> embodies <b>fragmentation</b> and <b>dislocation</b>, and is arguably no less visceral than this, but I feel it more ethical, because Abulhawa enacts violence on her characters who are already crushed under violences of the state of Israel and/or feelings of guilt, and also more truthful because I think it’s an illusion for me to think I can understand how Amal really feels.<br /><br />At times I felt THESE ARE NOT REAL CHARACTERS. There is a constellation of lives here, but most of them have only quirks (Huda’s habit of stating the obvious) rather than personalities. Mahjid, Amal’s husband, and, less so, Hasan, her father, are the only people apart from Amal who really came to life for me. Dalia’s characterisation does not transcend racialisation and an image of mental illness, despite Amal’s tenderness to her memory. Depictions of romantic love between Amal &amp; Mahjid and Yousef &amp; Fatima are intense, heartfelt and affecting, but highly conventional. There are no surprises in these relationships (apart from Hasan’s unorthodox marriage to the ‘bad Bedouin girl’). They are passionate and I believed in them, and that is enough to make the story work emotionally which unquestionably it does, but not to elevate it to the level of great literature like <i>The Woman from Tantoura</i>.<br /><br />An intergenerational structure is required to capture the biography of the invasion and onslaught against Palestine &amp; Palestinians. The lives of Yehya and Basima’s family are the pegs on which this story is hung. Thus, Abulhawa describes pivotal moments intensely and leaves long stretches blank. This blankness makes space for an effective description of the deadened and dislocated feeling of exile that Amal experiences in the USA. Although she makes some connections there, the sense of being cut off from the land she belongs to is debilitating, and the longing to return regardless of the high risks and terrible conditions is tangible.<br /><br />The long timeline also gives resonance to the beauty of certain moments and memories that take on ever deeper significance. A few months after being dispossessed from his land, Yehya sneaks back and returns with ‘a radiant spirit’ and pocketfuls of olives and other fruits of the harvest he has tended all his life. This stolen moment of jubilation blazes down the generations, a sign shining like tender winter sunshine for the right of return…</span>
  <a data-text-id="13545883017575425944" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


