  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2770115548" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2770115548" />
    <a title="Ahmed R. Rashwan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37690097-ahmed-r-rashwan"><img alt="Ahmed R. Rashwan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1541047821p2/37690097.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2770115548?book_show_action=true">Apr 02, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ahmed R. Rashwan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ahmed R. Rashwan" href="/user/show/37690097-ahmed-r-rashwan">Ahmed R. Rashwan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781408813553" href="/book/show/9394255-mornings-in-jenin">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2770115548" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18311187350954224331">It is heart-wrenching, emotional and torturous. How can my soul possibly be the same after reading this. A near perfect novel, flawed only be very subtle faults, it comes close to a perfect painting of Palestine. I assure you that you will lose yourself; it is a book that will confuse you. Amidst all the pain, gut-wrenching emotions and utter shock you will forget that this is a story of fiction and will almost believe it is most definitely an autobiography. The events are all too real; the scen</span>
  <span id="freeText18311187350954224331" style="display:none">It is heart-wrenching, emotional and torturous. How can my soul possibly be the same after reading this. A near perfect novel, flawed only be very subtle faults, it comes close to a perfect painting of Palestine. I assure you that you will lose yourself; it is a book that will confuse you. Amidst all the pain, gut-wrenching emotions and utter shock you will forget that this is a story of fiction and will almost believe it is most definitely an autobiography. The events are all too real; the scenery, the cities and devastation, all remnants of a not so distant past; a modern history written in blood. This is unmistakably accurate; that at least is <i>
  <b>not</b>
</i> a matter of debate.<br /><br />As a reader who was very genuinely moved by this and who was brought to heavy tears several times throughout the book, tears that almost transformed into sobs if not for my iron grip on my emotions, I can only imagine how Susan felt writing it, as she was much more closer to the story. It didn't even matter that I was in public. The beauty of such a story is that there is no need of raw talent, not that Susan Abulhawa lacks this in any way, to deliver such powerful story-telling, but it rather attains such power and strength from within its own self. No one can deny that these specific 300 pages are heavier in weight than any other 300 pages of any other book. That alone has catapulted this novel into the limelight; into the hearts of millions who feel deeply for this novel, even before ever reading it or opening its pages.<br /><br />How can we not feel shame, regret, guilt and remorse at the stories within this novel. How, when we have been intricately intertwined with the Palestinians, their land, their story and their cause ever since before childbirth. For years upon years, generations and generations, we have been connected intimately through religion, culture and tongue. In all sense of the word, we are one. But the heavy tears I cried were not weighed down by sadness and sorrow, but rather by utter helplessness and complete defeat. No matter where your allegiance now lies, what beliefs you have, and how you feel towards Arabs and Islam in general, this novel will put pressure on you, you will feel your heart compress under its unavoidable weight.<br /><br />I have thought long and hard about whether or not to disclose the flaws I felt the novel contained that left a small but noticeable scar on its masterpiece of a painting. I fear that in stating what I found was lacking in the novel that I would mistakenly give an incorrect idea about how I felt about this novel, and the deep emptiness it left inside of me upon its completion. But to keep in line with my harsh critique spirit and my straight-forwarded honesty, I feel it is my duty to mention the small kinks in the armor which this novel clearly is to the cause. <br /><br />Susan Abulhawa, although providing us here with a grandiose of a novel, an intimate, honest and passionate look at the Palestinian side of the notorious conflict tainted, I feel, the story by her repetitiveness and insistence on using specific phrases continuously throughout the novel; there are only so many times you can read a sentence or a phrase before it loses its meaning or impact. The switching back and forth between different narrators and actual narrative styles (first person, third person) was slightly confusing at times and left me wondering why Abulhawa couldn't simply just stick to one type. <br /><br />On another note, Susan's Abulhawa's insistence on referring to the Palestinians as Arabs, and sort of insinuating throughout the novel that Arab and Muslim were synonymous was completely out of place here. The narrative would have been much more impactful if it was more geographically (and historically) accurate. Here is where Susan's Palestinian bias shines the brightest. I am by no means on Israel's side in this conflict, but it is clear that to Susan, Jews and Israelis are also as synonymous as Arabs and Muslims; an incorrect assumption in both matters. Canaanites and Judaism on the other hand, can definitely be considered synonymous, as Canaanites held Judaism as a religion in the geographical area of Palestine far more than Islam had been. Palestinians only identified as Arabs after the Arab conquest, which in itself was an usurpation of a people and their culture. A biased mind would clearly ascertain that the Jews had as much of a right to the land as Muslims believe they do, and Canaanite culture had as much of a right to the land as anyone who identifies as Arab believe they do, but <i>
  <b>CLEARLY</b>
</i> not condoning the method in which Israelis went about affirming that.<br /><br />But as has been mentioned, these faults can barely be considered so and were only noticeable to my very scrutinizing eyes. There should be no doubt in anyone's mind that this is a must read novel. If one were to pick up one novel, summarizing the Palestinian conflict from the Palestinian point of view, this would definitely be the most moving, accurate and representative novel to date. Although this book was originally written in English, I can only imagine the magnificent impact it would create in one's heart and soul if read in the story and its character's native language. If you are accepting of a punch in the gut, a squeeze of your heart and a grip of your soul; this is definitely a book that should be on anyone's to read list.</span>
  <a data-text-id="18311187350954224331" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

